\begin_layout Subsubsection
Feynman diagrams
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Loop diagrams can be used to represent traces.
 Notice that there are two types of loops (traces): 
\emph on
external loops
\emph default
 with either one or two external vertices and 
\emph on
internal loops
\emph default
 coming from 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{\text{int}})^{L}$
\end_inset

 (refer to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S_int"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

]).
 Wick's theorem tells us that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Gaussian average
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an even number of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 is the sum of all possible pair contractions, which defines the RPA propagator
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}}=\big[S_{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}}^{(2)}\big]^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{N}D_{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}}=\int D[\bar{\phi},\phi]\Delta\bar{\phi}_{\alpha_{1}}\Delta\phi_{\alpha_{2}}e^{-N(\Delta\bar{\phi}_{\alpha}S_{\alpha\alpha'}^{(2)}\Delta\phi_{\alpha'})}.\label{eq:RPA_pro}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the linked-cluster theorem, due to the presence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 in the denominator for both 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha\beta}^{(\text{I})}(1,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha\beta}^{(\text{II})}(1,2)$
\end_inset

, only connected diagrams contribute to the dynamical spin susceptibility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From now on, we use open/closed dots to represent external/internal vertices,
 straight/wavy lines to represent the saddle point/RPA propagators, and
 dot line for the external sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The recipes to construct diagrams for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha\beta}^{(\text{I})}(1,2)$
\end_inset

 are given as following: 1.
 choose one external loop with two external vertices and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0)$
\end_inset

 internal vertices; 2.
 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 internal loops; 3.
 contract all wavy lines.
 As for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha\beta}^{(\text{II})}(1,2)$
\end_inset

 , step 2, 3 are the same, the only difference is step 1: choose two external
 loops each with one external vertex and some internal vertices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that external loops are of the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}[N^{0}]$
\end_inset

, while each internal loop is of the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}[N^{1}]$
\end_inset

